independently implementing and owning the zaura_surface object to

using the WaylandZAuraSurface wrapper owned by WaylandSurface.



This simplifies the implementation of the extension interface

client-side. The surface extension is now owned directly by the

WaylandSurface (as with other surface extensions). This makes

lifetime easier to reason about and makes extensions to commit

state easier to integrate with WaylandSurface::State.



WaylandWindow has been made a WaylandZAuraSurface::Delegate these

methods are overridden by the window subclasses as needed to handle

surface extension events from the server.

entry.title: Make partitioned service workers only send cookies from their partition
entry.content:
Before this change, workers would use partitioned cookies from their own site's partition in network requests from service workers. This could allow sites to join state across different partitions.



For first-party partitioned/unpartitioned workers, the resulting IsolationInfo's top-level and current origin is the worker origin. Site for cookies ends up being the site of the worker origin.



For third-party partitioned workers, the top-level origin is derived from StorageKey's top-frame site. In these contexts, SFC is null.



This CL does *not* ensure partitioning bounds for cookies sent in service worker script requests. I will be adding that in a follow-up CL.

entry.title: Adjust Rust crate metadata handling
entry.content:
A crate metadata "hash" can be provided to rustc to disambiguate

libraries with the same name but different versions or

configuration. The hash is included in generated symbol names,

disambiguating the same function name as called from different

dependencies. Note this doesn't allow including two crates of the same

name directly. It just prevent conflicts from internal uses or

re-exported declarations of a function from a crate of the same name.



Cargo's hashes are influenced by crate version, among other

things. This way foo v2 and v3 can coexist in the same final artifact

without confusion.



Importantly, the Rust libstd build uses this to ensure internal uses

of a dependency don't conflict with downstream users of libstd. We

want to do the same for the GN-hosted std build.



With this CL, the metadata is both passed to rustc, to influence crate

metadata information when compiling, and is appended to the generated

library name, so linker invocations don't get confused. The

rustc_metadata option is exposed by rust_target so we can (sparingly)

use this in first party targets.



cargo_crate now passes rustc_metadata to rust_target instead of

passing the crate epoch. rust_target no longer needs to know about

"epoch"s which should be used only for third-party crates, not

first-party targetes.



A lot of test targets are added due to how nuanced this is, and how

easily it can go wrong. rlibs, rust exectuables, C++ executables

including rust, etc should all build correctly even with this change.

entry.title: Fix Rust build when use_clang_coverage = true
entry.content:
Building Rust code with use_clang_coverage=true was broken due to the

libstd build not taking it into account. profiler_builtins and its

dependencies (core, compiler_builtins, libc) can't be built with

instrumentation since it would be a circular dependency.



The solution is to simply build those crates without

instrumentation. The rest of libstd, and all other Rust code, can

build with instrumentation.



Most of this CL is changes to gnrt to plumb this configuration from

gnrt_config.toml.

entry.title: [wayland] Create WaylandZAuraSurface client-side wrapper
entry.content:
This CL introduces a wrapper class for the client-side zaura_surface

object. It encapsulates the events and requests defined in

zaura_surface's definition.



The intention is to factor out the zaura_surface implementation from

the WaylandToplevelWindow and WaylandPopup subclasses.



Follow up CLs will integrate this extension wrapper into the existing

WaylandSurface class. This cleans up the code and makes the lifetimes

of the extension clearer (strictly a subset of the lifetime of the

entry.title: Simplify PasswordManagerLauncher's requirements.
entry.content:
This change:

- replaces Activity with Context; the PasswordManagerLauncher needs

Activity, but passes it to PasswordManagerHelper as Context.

- replaces ModalDialogManager ObservableSupplier with just Supplier.

Nowhere in the call chain was the Observable aspect needed.

- Defers to Tab and WindowAndroid to retrieve necessary bits,

allowing us to drop the requirement to have access to the

ModalDialogManager supplier.



The change passes SearchActivity's tab as well. That tab is

non-interactable, similarly to the Phone's TabSwitcher. In both cases

we do not want to attempt to load URLs in these cases.



This is guaranteed to work - at least on the Omnibox side. We rely on

the availability of the Tab a lot - whether to initiate the navigation

or present the Delete dialog. Omnibox's Autocomplete requires a tab to

function and is not offered in an environment where no Tabs are

present.



Resolving the HistoryClustersCoordinator dependency will allow us to

fully decouple the ActionChipsDelegate and move it to the Omnibox

source location.

entry.title: TTS: Give the TTS sandbox read access to /proc/cpuinfo
entry.content:
A recent CL [1] changed the custom fused LSTM operator that was used for

TTS and made it use the XNNPack LSTM operator. This improved TTS latency

but inadvertently caused a breakage in TTS on ChromeOS where no speech

output was being produced. The root cause is that XNNPack relies on

cpuinfo to initialize, but this was disallowed by the TTS sandbox.

This change fixes the issue by giving the TTS sandbox read access to

/proc/cpuinfo.



Document [2] gives more details on proposed solutions and alternatives

considered. Patchset 4 of this change shows an attempt at the

preferred approach, which was to initialize cpuinfo before the TTS

sandbox sets up; however, patchset 4 didn't fix the issue and I tried

other variations of patchset 4 (e.g. moving the initialization to

different locations), but could not get it working. As a result, we

are falling back to this approach, which has been LGTM'd by security.



See document [2] for more details and general discussion on this issue.



[1] cl/504234267

entry.title: Fix handling of allowlisted spoof-check-failing domains
entry.content:
Domains that fail IDN spoof checking are allowlisted in a slightly

special way in that they're part of a cohort with only themselves (since

not having a cohort indicates that the domain can spoof anyone). This CL

aligns the implementation with the design intent.

builds, this means we no longer fail a DCHECK.

rects (Lacros) because we're aiming to "overlay" every quad every frame.

entry.title: Correctly account for shared memory in ArrayBufferContents
entry.content:
When an ArrayBufferContents is created from shared memory, we use

PlatformSharedMemoryHandle::MapAt to map the shared memory into the

virtual address space, and this will also account for the new mapping in

the SharedMemorySecurityPolicy. However, when we later unmap the shared

memory mapping again, we were previously directly using the

SharedMemoryMapper, and so the unmapping was not accounted for in the

SharedMemorySecurityPolicy. This CL fixes that by introducing a new

PlatformSharedMemoryRegion::Unmap helper function that performs the

accounting and forwards to the provided SharedMemoryMapper to do the

actual unmapping of the shared memory pages.
